Lists all the available symbol libraries. If you want the user-defined symbol libraries to be displayed here, you need to specify them by choosing Tools > Options in the Diamond window and selecting User Defined Symbol Library from Schematic Editor options.

Select a library file from this list, and the symbols within that library will be displayed in the Symbol List below it.
Lists all the symbols within the selected library file. Click to select one of them, and the symbol is attached to your mouse cursor. Click the desired location in your schematic to place the symbol.

dialog.name: find
dialog.whatsthis: Specifies the type and name of the object that you want to find. Wildcards are supported.
Lists the find results in alphabetical order. You can then click any item in the list to highlight it in the Schematic Editor window.
Finds the specified items and lists them in the Find Results box.

dialog.name: object_properties
dialog.whatsthis: Lists the sheet, wires, and symbol instances that are currently selected in the Schematic Editor window. Click one item in the list to show its attributes in the right-hand table.

Limits the attributes displayed in the table below it. Type a string (wildcards are supported) that includes the characters you want to include and click Go. To recover the original list, erase the string in the edit box and click Go.

Lists the available attributes for the sheet, wire, or symbol instance selected in the Category box. The attributes are listed in alphabetical order. To specify an attribute value, double-click the Value cell, enter the new value, and click Apply.

Sheet number and size are not editable in this dialog box. To edit sheet attributes, use the Sheet command on the Edit menu.
Clears the selected attribute value.
Resets the selected attribute to its original value.
Applies the attribute settings in this dialog box.
dialog.description: Indicates the bounding box or the area for a given UGROUP. Given in number of rows and columns. Convention: BBOX= H,W
Tells Precision RTL Synthesis that the module should not be compiled or optimized. Only the interface need be defined for synthesis.
Attach to a DELAY element to set a coarse delay with CDEL delay parameters.
Attach to a block to specify a name for the device component that is created when the block is mapped. Convention: COMP(PLC)=comp_name
Attach to a DCS element to set the mode.
Specifies the delay type on the DELAY element.
The differential current-source type driver has programmable output current in each mode of operation.
Attach to input or output buffers (such as IB or OB) to provide differential termination.
Instructs map to pack a DIN/DOUT register into PIO/IOLOGIC sites. Convention: DIN= signal_name
Tells Precision RTL Synthesis to pass the module through synthesis without optimizing or unmapping.
Instructs map to pack a DIN/DOUT register into PIO/IOLOGIC sites. Convention: DOUT= signal_name
Obsolete. Use Spreadsheet View to apply the TO keyword in the BLOCK, MAXDELAY, and MULTICYCLE constraints instead.
Attach to a DELAY element to set a fine delay with FDEL delay parameters.
Enables or disables the global set/reset for registered elements such as registers, PLLs, and memories.
Groups components that are to be instantiated multiple times. Convention: HGROUP= identifier
Tells Precision RTL Synthesis to maintain the hierarchy of the module.
Indicates the physical location of the northwest corner of an HGROUP or UGROUP assignment. Convention: HULOC = row#col#
Indicates the northwest corner of a region for a given HGROUP or UGROUP definition. Convention: HURLOC = row#col#
Sets the on-chip programmable output impedance.
Attach to output and bidirectional buffers to connect to ground.
Attach to output and bidirectional buffers to connect to high.
INBUF is a global setting. All unused input buffers are disabled when INBUF is OFF to save power.
Attach to an output buffer to modify loading on outputs from the default 50 pF for timing analysis. Convention: LOAD= xx.xx
Specifies a site location for the component that is created when this block is mapped. Convention: LOC= site_name
Tells Precision RTL Synthesis that an instance should not be optimized or changed.
Prevents re-timing on the hierarchy of the instance. Convention: NORETIME= string
Attach to input combinations to reduce the common mode range.
Indicates the area size a region. Convention: RBBOX = H,W
Allows you to choose this internal reference circuit or an external one.
Indicates the region to which a given HGROUP or UGROUP belongs. Convention: REGION = identifier
Attach to an output buffer or pad to specify the relative speed (slew rate) of the output driver, with 1 indicating the slowest and 100 the fastest.
Tells Synplify Pro to treat the module as a black box during synthesis.
Tells Synplify Pro how to control the amount of hierarchical transformation that occurs across boundaries on module or component instances during optimization.
Tells Synplify Pro whether or not to generate the hierarchy in the EDIF output when assigned to the top-level module of your design. The default (true) is to allow hierarchy generation.
Tells Synplify Pro to treat the ports of a design unit as individual signals (scalars), not as buses (arrays) in the EDIF file.
Tells Synplify Pro whether or not to remove instances that have outputs that are not driven.
Specifies the on-chip parallel input and output termination.
Specifies the on-chip parallel input and output termination.
Specifies the on-chip input parallel termination to VTT.
Universal grouping construct. Convention: UGROUP = identifier
Attach to input buffer elements (such as IB) to enable a common mode voltage.
Blocks timing analysis on the net when PAR or TRACE performs a timing analysis on the design. Convention: BLOCKNET= name
This attribute is placed on a net or group of nets and defines a bus structure. Convention: BUS= name
Attach to bidirectional and output buffers (such as BB, BBPD, OB, and OBW) to set the drive strength attribute for output standards that support programmable drive strength.
Use to achieve zero hold time for the input registers when a direct drive primary clock (no PLL) is employed.
Attach to a clock net to identify the minimum operating frequency for all sequential output to sequential input pins clocked by the specified net. Convention: FREQUENCY= value
Sets the I/O standard for an I/O (such as IB, OB, and BB). Convention: IO_TYPE= buffer type
Identifies a maximum total delay for a net, bus, or path in the design. Convention: MAXDELAY= value
Specifies that the net or instance cannot be removed as unused logic.
Specifies that the net cannot be absorbed into a logic block when the design is mapped. Convention: NOMERGE = net_name
Tells Precision RTL Synthesis to not place an I/O pad on the specified port when the design is mapped to the technology.
You can assign OPENDRAIN to all the LVCMOS and LVTTL standards. OFF is the default.
Turns on the programmable PCI clamp diode.
Attach to a clock net to identify a clock period for all pins clocked by the specified net. Convention: PERIOD = value
Tells Precision RTL Synthesis to preserve the specified signal and the driver in the design. Specifies that both a signal and the signal name must survive synthesis.
Tells Precision RTL Synthesis to preserve the specified signal in the design.
Attach to output buffer elements (such as OB and OBW) and bidirectional buffers to specify a pullup or pulldown mode: UP, DOWN, NONE, KEEPER, PCICLAMP.
Attach to all output buffers (such as OB and OBW) and bidirectional buffers to specify a fast or slow slew rate.
Obsolete. Use Spreadsheet View to apply the FROM keyword in the BLOCK, CLOCK_TO_OUT, MAXDELAY, and MULTICYCLE constraints instead.
Tells Synplify Pro to use the signal as the enable input to an enable flip-flop when multiple candidates are possible.
Tells Synplify Pro to enable or disable I/O insertion on a port level or a global level.
Tells Synplify Pro to not remove the internal signal during synthesis and optimization.
Tells Synplify Pro the fanout limit for an individual input port or register output.
Tells Synplify Pro to disable automatic clock buffer insertion.
Tells Synplify Pro to prevent sequential optimizations across a flip-flop boundary during optimization, and preserves the signal.
Tells Synplify Pro to pack flip-flops in the I/O ring to improve input/output path timing.

dialog.name: sheet
dialog.whatsthis: Lists all the sheets currently defined and their sheet size.
Moves up the selected sheet one position. This changes the order in which sheet tabs are displayed at the bottom of the Schematic Editor window.
Moves down the selected sheet one position. This changes the order in which sheet tabs are displayed at the bottom of the Schematic Editor window.
Opens a dialog box for resizing the selected sheet. Select a new sheet size and click OK.
Opens a dialog box showing the number of the currently selected sheet. Type a new number and click OK.

Opens a dialog box for adding a new sheet. Select a sheet size from the Sheet Size box. Enter a sheet number. This number does not have to be in sequence. For example, you can have sheet numbers of 1, 2, 3, 6, 8, 9, and so on.
Deletes the selected sheet.
If your sheets are not in a close sequence, for example 1, 2, 5, 7, 9, click this button and they will be resequenced as 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.

dialog.name: options
dialog.whatsthis: Controls whether the Grid is displayed. The grid appears as dots, with one dot at every grid intersection. Every tenth grid point is larger. As you zoom out and the grid points get closer, some grid dots might not be displayed.

There are two line weights for drawing lines and rectangles. Select this option to use the heavier weight. Wide lines have the same weight as buses on schematics. This setting affects only the lines to be added, not the existing lines.

This dialog box allows you to specify your own libraries (.lib) of schematic symbols. The specified libraries will appear in Schematic Editor's Add Symbol dialog box so that you can add the symbols included in the library to a schematic.

To add a user library, click New and browse for the .lib file that you want to add. To remove a library, select the library file in the list and click Delete. You can also use the Up and Down buttons to adjust library file order.
